Following the hint, we multiply both sides by the integrating factor
$e^{-2t}$ to get

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle e^{-2t}\frac{dy}{dt} - 2ye^{-2t} = 4e^{-2t} + e^{t}
\end{align*}

The point of the integrating factor is that we can now express the left
hand side as simple derivative:

\begin{align*}
e^{-2t}\frac{dy}{dt} - 2ye^{-2t} = \displaystyle (ye^{-2t})'
\end{align*}

Plugging this into the initial equation above we find

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle (ye^{-2t})' = 4e^{-2t} + e^{t}
\end{align*}

and by integrating both sides we obtain

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle ye^{-2t} = -2e^{-2t} + e^{t} + C
\end{align*}

Solving for \emph{y} yields

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle y = -2 + e^{3t} + Ce^{2t}
\end{align*}

completing the question.

